basement living room before + after.

   Hi friends! I thought I‚Äôd take this lazy Sunday to show you a room
   makeover, as well as a mini gallery wall project I finished a few
   months back, which you saw a sneak peek over on my Facebook last week.

   But let me give you a bit of background on this room first‚Ä¶

   When we moved into our house, the basement was considered ‚Äúfinished,‚Äù
   but you‚Äôd never guess it by looking at the cold cement floors (covered
   with accent rugs), stark white walls and the surplus of cobwebs, not to
   mention all of previous home owners‚Äô furniture and decor that wasn‚Äôt
   living up to the room‚Äôs potential.

   Within the first week of moving in, we did a cleaning overhaul, threw
   some some color up on one of the walls for a pop, and had carpet
   installed from Lowe‚Äôs. The next phase was finding furniture that best
   fit the space (there‚Äôs already been some changes, including the coffee
   table switch-out which you saw here, and a chair swap which you‚Äôll see
   below), and my favorite ‚Äî adding in decor!

   So are you ready to see how this space has transformed? Take a look!

   BEFORE (MLS listing) PICS:

   basement3 basement2    basement1 basement4

   PROGRESS PICS:

   029 002   024 026

   Above shows what the room looked like a few months after we moved in.
   It was definitely an improvement from the ‚Äòbefore‚Äô state, but it still
   didn‚Äôt have that ‚Äúfinished‚Äù feeling and I soon realized a few of my
   furnishing choices (i.e. bulky coffee table and swivel tub chair)
   weren‚Äôt helping any. Fast-forward to today‚Ä¶

   NOW PICS:

   basement

   You already saw ^this picture^ from the trunk makeover post, but I went
   ahead and took some of the other sides of the room so you could see the
   full monty.

   basement

   basement bar

basement

   ^cafe curtains disguise the electronic storage area and the ‚ÄòLOVE‚Äô wall
   art conceals the electric panel.

   reading nook

   ^need an ottoman? turn a wicker basket or wooden crate upside down and
   add a pillow!

   The main goal for this space was to make it a hang out area
   which people actually want to hang out in, unlike before. This was
   achieved by giving warmth to the room with a simple carpet install,
   adding floor-length curtains (despite the small windows), making it
   feel homey with the right use of furniture and decor, and of course ‚Äî
   adding in the ‚Äúfun‚Äù hang-out features, i.e. a bar, mounted TV and
   surround sound.

   As you probably could‚Äôve guessed, I‚Äôm not calling this room ‚Äúcomplete‚Äù
   by any means because there will always be an impending project just
   waiting to happen‚Ä¶ Some ideas include painting the cabinetry below the
   TV, giving the countertop some sort of treatment (cement, perhaps?),
   and/or changing the accent wall to a new color. I‚Äôll keep you posted!

   Check back again soon!

